<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-338-451  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 338 451.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Feb 13 1989 n404 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Copyright law extended to microcode. (Intel Corp.'s lawsuitagainst NEC Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thompson, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The microcode to Intel Corp's 8086 and 8088 microprocessors isprotected by US copyright law, finds US District Court JudgeWilliam Gray in a settlement of Intel's long-standing suit againstNEC Corp. The decision is the first to extend copyright protectionto microcode.andP;  Intel VP Tom Dunlap says the ruling has broadconnotations providing protection for anything that acts as a setof instructions.andP;  NEC lawyer Alan MacPherson claims the decisionalso recognizes that much function-related code is notcopyrighted.andP;  The ruling points out that certain similarities inIntel and NEC codes are inevitable as both implementDOS-compatible instruction sets.andP;  Intel forfeited its rights on8086 and 8088 chips by failing to police the marking of its claimon second-sourced chips, the ruling states.andP;  More important toIntel, however, is protection for its 80286 and 80386 microcodes,which are registered under separate copyrights.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intel Corp. (cases)NEC Corp. (cases).andO;Ticker:    INTC; NIPNY.andO;Product:   Intel 8086 (Microprocessor) (cases)Intel 8088 (Microprocessor) (cases).andO;Topic:     CopyrightMicrocodeMicroprocessorsLaw SuitLegal IssuesCourt CasesInstruction Sets.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>